1
00:00:00,700 --> 00:00:02,850
Take a look at this chart.

2
00:00:02,850 --> 00:00:08,870
This is one of the most common traps used
by smart money to fool both buyers, and sellers,

3
00:00:08,870 --> 00:00:10,840
at the same time.

4
00:00:10,840 --> 00:00:13,630
You probably faced this yourself.

5
00:00:13,630 --> 00:00:19,920
Market breaks a swing high, you think is a
breakout, but instead of continuing higher,

6
00:00:19,920 --> 00:00:24,530
it aggressively moves lower, also breaking
a recent swing low.

7
00:00:24,530 --> 00:00:28,240
Basically, a double liquidity clear-out.

8
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:31,270
It happens every day, on all time frames.

9
00:00:31,270 --> 00:00:36,580
And if you identify it correctly, it might
be one of the best smart money setups to trade.

10
00:00:36,580 --> 00:00:38,730
Let’s talk about this.

11
00:00:38,730 --> 00:00:43,649
You know the drill, like, subscribe, and stick
around for the full video.

12
00:00:43,649 --> 00:00:52,090
The Double Liquidity Clear-out TRAP
It all starts with a breakout that fails to

13
00:00:52,090 --> 00:00:56,900
continue beyond a level, resulting in a ‘false’
breakout.

14
00:00:56,900 --> 00:01:01,710
False breakout patterns are one of the most
important price action patterns to learn,

15
00:01:01,710 --> 00:01:07,280
because a false-break is often a very strong
indication that a momentum move might start

16
00:01:07,280 --> 00:01:08,750
soon.

17
00:01:08,750 --> 00:01:13,690
Trading is a game of deceptions and traps,
and you must learn to play accordingly.

18
00:01:13,690 --> 00:01:20,641
So, firstly, price will break a swing high,
but then it quickly reverses, deceiving all

19
00:01:20,641 --> 00:01:23,680
buyers who took the ‘bait’ of the breakout.

20
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:29,740
It’s often the case that amateurs will enter
what looks like an ‘obvious’ breakout.

21
00:01:29,740 --> 00:01:33,820
Then the professionals will push the market
back the other way.

22
00:01:33,820 --> 00:01:36,649
This is the first liquidity clear-out.

23
00:01:36,649 --> 00:01:40,950
The second part of the pattern consists in
another trap.

24
00:01:40,950 --> 00:01:47,390
Price will fall and will break a swing low,
this time trapping traders on the short side.

25
00:01:47,390 --> 00:01:53,880
This is the second liquidity clear-out, designed
to trap the ‘weak hands’ in the market.

26
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:59,350
This include traders that take positions when
a market is already quite extended or they

27
00:01:59,350 --> 00:02:04,750
try to ‘predict’ a breakout from a key
support level too early.

28
00:02:04,750 --> 00:02:08,700
Smart money of course watch for these missteps
by the amateurs.

29
00:02:08,700 --> 00:02:14,610
As a price action trader, you want to learn
how to use this double liquidity clear-out

30
00:02:14,610 --> 00:02:18,960
to your advantage, rather than falling victim
to it.

31
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:24,580
From my backtests, after I spot this double
liquidity clear-out setup, I try to find a

32
00:02:24,580 --> 00:02:28,230
trade in the direction of the initial false
breakout.

33
00:02:28,230 --> 00:02:31,420
It’s basically a trend continuation setup.

34
00:02:31,420 --> 00:02:37,320
Don’t get me wrong, it takes discipline
and a bit of ‘gut feel’ to know when this

35
00:02:37,320 --> 00:02:43,250
pattern is likely to occur, and you can never
really know ‘for sure’ until after the

36
00:02:43,250 --> 00:02:46,390
second liquidity clear-out has formed.

37
00:02:46,390 --> 00:02:52,150
But when you find it, the high probability
trade is in the direction of the initial breakout.

38
00:02:52,150 --> 00:02:58,420
Both buyers and sellers are trapped in losing
positions

39
00:02:58,420 --> 00:03:04,120
The double fake out pattern occurs in all
market conditions; trending, consolidating,

40
00:03:04,120 --> 00:03:10,530
counter-trend, but, from my experience, the
best way to trade it is in-line with a dominant

41
00:03:10,530 --> 00:03:11,890
trend.

42
00:03:11,890 --> 00:03:17,290
Have you ever been stopped out, only to see
price reverse from that very same level?

43
00:03:17,290 --> 00:03:20,370
I’m sure you have and you’re not alone.

44
00:03:20,370 --> 00:03:25,930
Many traders tend to place their stops in
the same types of places, without sufficiently

45
00:03:25,930 --> 00:03:29,709
weighing the fact that they are incredibly
easy to hit.

46
00:03:29,709 --> 00:03:37,061
In this chart, we have a clear downtrend in
place and a double liquidity clear-out, first

47
00:03:37,061 --> 00:03:44,880
to the downside, then, to the upside, within
a larger downtrend trend.

48
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:50,610
When you have the second trap, baiting buyers
in the market, where movement is against a

49
00:03:50,610 --> 00:03:56,020
dominant trend like this, it’s usually a
very good signal that the trend may be ready

50
00:03:56,020 --> 00:03:59,390
to resume to the downside.

51
00:03:59,390 --> 00:04:06,000
Amateur traders love to try to pick the bottom
in a downtrend or the top in an uptrend, and

52
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,060
most of them are happy to trade a reversal,
instead of a continuation.

53
00:04:11,060 --> 00:04:18,280
On each of these false-breakouts in this example,
2 different types of traders were trapped.

54
00:04:18,280 --> 00:04:24,400
First, traders that entered short when the
market was making a new low and the second

55
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:30,210
batch of traders that thought the downtrend
was over and so they started buying.

56
00:04:30,210 --> 00:04:37,910
So initial sellers were removed from the market,
as their stops were probably around the area

57
00:04:37,910 --> 00:04:40,360
where buyers anticipated a breakout.

58
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:46,479
Buyers were also trapped after the second
liquidity clear-out.

59
00:04:46,479 --> 00:04:51,330
And then professionals took advantage of the
temporary strength within the down-trending

60
00:04:51,330 --> 00:04:59,220
market and entered short from value, and then
the downtrend resumed, flushing out all those

61
00:04:59,220 --> 00:05:02,530
amateur traders with weak positions.

62
00:05:02,530 --> 00:05:11,240
Enter after the second liquidity clear-out
You want to position yourself after the second

63
00:05:11,240 --> 00:05:17,020
liquidity clear-out, in line with the smart
money and with the dominant trend.

64
00:05:17,020 --> 00:05:24,430
I can’t give you an exact entry, but price
action is again your best friend.

65
00:05:24,430 --> 00:05:30,960
When price returns inside the previous range,
after the second liquidity clear-out, and

66
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:36,590
there’s no momentum to the upside, you have
to find some sort of signal to enter.

67
00:05:36,590 --> 00:05:43,949
In this case I see a double top and a bearish
engulfing candle, offering several clues that

68
00:05:43,949 --> 00:05:46,250
the downtrend might resume.

69
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:53,090
You could also add a 20 moving average, and
trade when price moves below it.

70
00:05:53,090 --> 00:05:58,630
There are many methods to enter, you just
have to choose the one you feel most comfortable

71
00:05:58,630 --> 00:05:59,630
with.

72
00:05:59,630 --> 00:06:00,630
Expect liquidity clear-outs when a market
is stuck in a range

73
00:06:00,630 --> 00:06:11,919
The double liquidity clear-out pattern is
very common in trading ranges because inexperienced

74
00:06:11,919 --> 00:06:16,449
traders often try to pick the breakout of
the range.

75
00:06:16,449 --> 00:06:22,320
However, price may stay range-bound for longer
than most assume.

76
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:27,240
Knowing that liquidity clear-outs are somewhat
common when a market is stuck in a trading

77
00:06:27,240 --> 00:06:31,810
range is a very valuable piece of information.

78
00:06:31,810 --> 00:06:36,990
Trading this setup in a range-bound market
can be very lucrative as you can wait for

79
00:06:36,990 --> 00:06:43,919
liquidity clear-outs at both the support or
resistance boundary of the range, and then

80
00:06:43,919 --> 00:06:49,289
trade back in the direction of the first false
breakout.

81
00:06:49,289 --> 00:06:51,889
It sounds easy in theory, I know.

82
00:06:51,889 --> 00:06:56,870
The best way to be sure you don’t get caught
in the second false-breakout, when you plan

83
00:06:56,870 --> 00:07:02,509
to enter, is to simply wait for price to close
inside of the range.

84
00:07:02,509 --> 00:07:09,020
If this happens, there’s a good chance the
pattern is completed and price is then going

85
00:07:09,020 --> 00:07:10,390
to start trending again.

86
00:07:10,390 --> 00:07:15,230
Pin bars and candles with large wicks

87
00:07:15,230 --> 00:07:22,990
With this setup, pin bars and candles with
large wicks will help you to identify the

88
00:07:22,990 --> 00:07:27,500
liquidity clear-outs and will also help you
to time your entry.

89
00:07:27,500 --> 00:07:33,570
Let’s look at his EUR/USD chart, on the
hourly time frames.

90
00:07:33,570 --> 00:07:39,879
At a quick glance I see not 1, but 2 obvious
setups.

91
00:07:39,879 --> 00:07:43,419
The first one is here.

92
00:07:43,419 --> 00:07:51,289
Liquidity clear-out, reversal, buyers are
trapped, liquidity clear-out, sellers are

93
00:07:51,289 --> 00:07:57,069
trapped and price continues in the initial
direction.

94
00:07:57,069 --> 00:08:00,330
And the second one here.

95
00:08:00,330 --> 00:08:08,151
Liquidity clear-out, sellers are trapped,
reversal, second liquidity clear-out, this

96
00:08:08,151 --> 00:08:15,879
time, buyers are trapped and price continues
its recent downtrend.

97
00:08:15,879 --> 00:08:18,400
Both setups have one thing in common.

98
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:20,720
Can you identify it?

99
00:08:20,720 --> 00:08:26,759
We have candles with large wicks during the
second liquidity clear-out, on both occasions.

100
00:08:26,759 --> 00:08:35,810
A price action trader can use this false breakout
pin bar signal to trade the setup.

101
00:08:35,810 --> 00:08:42,269
First we get the bullish pin bar at the bottom
of this liquidity clear-out.

102
00:08:42,269 --> 00:08:48,899
This pin would have looked like the big bearish
candle, baiting sellers to enter the market.

103
00:08:48,899 --> 00:08:53,400
A lot of traders shorted the market when the
candle was forming.

104
00:08:53,400 --> 00:08:59,250
And I know that if the market was to move
higher from here, at some point the traders

105
00:08:59,250 --> 00:09:05,120
who have sold during this pin are likely to
close their trade.

106
00:09:05,120 --> 00:09:06,339
The same here.

107
00:09:06,339 --> 00:09:13,040
Before this pin bar became a pin bar it was
actually a large range candle.

108
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:18,930
And if you watched my previous video about
common market traps, you know that large range

109
00:09:18,930 --> 00:09:26,260
candles are the types of candle which traders
will use to jump into trading positions.

110
00:09:26,260 --> 00:09:32,700
The price made a large up move which seduce
lots of traders into placing trades in the

111
00:09:32,700 --> 00:09:38,950
direction of the candle, the sudden increase
in buy orders means smart money are now able

112
00:09:38,950 --> 00:09:45,680
to complete a trading action such as taking
profits or placing more trades.

113
00:09:45,680 --> 00:09:51,120
When smart money make their decision, all
of the orders which were coming into the market

114
00:09:51,120 --> 00:09:58,230
from the traders placing trades in the direction
of the candle are consumed and the price moves

115
00:09:58,230 --> 00:10:00,600
in the opposite direction.

116
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:05,709
And because these actions pushed the price
in the opposite direction to which buyers

117
00:10:05,709 --> 00:10:11,870
had placed their trades, it means their positions
are currently at a loss.

118
00:10:11,870 --> 00:10:17,660
In both cases, if you want to profit from
these trapped traders, a pin bar will make

119
00:10:17,660 --> 00:10:20,779
it easier to place your trade.

120
00:10:20,779 --> 00:10:28,110
You set the stop loss, below the bullish pin
bar here, and above the bearish pin bar, here.

121
00:10:28,110 --> 00:10:32,630
The psychology behind the double liquidity
pattern

122
00:10:32,630 --> 00:10:40,720
It is important to understand the psychology
behind this double liquidity pattern and why

123
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:48,829
it often reveals that smart money might be
behind buying and not retail "weak hands".

124
00:10:48,829 --> 00:10:55,240
After the first aggressive liquidity clear-out,
many retail traders don’t think of buying,

125
00:10:55,240 --> 00:10:57,300
if anything the opposite.

126
00:10:57,300 --> 00:11:04,610
The magnitude of fresh selling could discourage
buying and trigger selling instead (many traders

127
00:11:04,610 --> 00:11:08,920
start thinking about abandoning their prior
long positions).

128
00:11:08,920 --> 00:11:14,709
If someone is actually strongly buying after
the second liquidity clear-out, it is more

129
00:11:14,709 --> 00:11:18,260
likely than it isn’t a retail participant.

130
00:11:18,260 --> 00:11:25,519
This gives you insight that someone bigger
is willing to defend this area.

131
00:11:25,519 --> 00:11:30,500
After you have been on the wrong side of a
market a few times, you will begin to realize

132
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:36,089
that this double fakeout can actually provide
high quality tradable opportunities.

133
00:11:36,089 --> 00:11:43,680
The reality is that classic technical analysis,
teached in most trading books, is kinda outdated.

134
00:11:43,680 --> 00:11:49,040
And you should design your trading strategy
around these types of scenarios.

135
00:11:49,040 --> 00:11:54,540
Some of the best trades occur when market
players become trapped and begin to cover

136
00:11:54,540 --> 00:11:56,800
their losing trades.

137
00:11:56,800 --> 00:12:02,779
Accumulation, manipulation and trend phase.

138
00:12:02,779 --> 00:12:09,639
If you have trouble finding this pattern,
try to break it into 3 stages: accumulation,

139
00:12:09,639 --> 00:12:13,500
manipulation, and the trend phase.

140
00:12:13,500 --> 00:12:18,790
Accumulation is the stage where smart money
enter their positions, manipulation is the

141
00:12:18,790 --> 00:12:25,089
stage where the first and the second liquidity
clear out appear, and after the traders are

142
00:12:25,089 --> 00:12:30,120
trapped, the trend phase begins.

143
00:12:30,120 --> 00:12:34,470
The first thing you need to identify is the
accumulation.

144
00:12:34,470 --> 00:12:37,410
Sometimes is obvious, sometimes in not.

145
00:12:37,410 --> 00:12:43,709
Banks either enter the market by accumulating
a long position which they will later sell

146
00:12:43,709 --> 00:12:52,220
at a higher price, or a short position which
they will later buy back at a lower price.

147
00:12:52,220 --> 00:12:57,690
If you can identify the price levels where
banks are accumulating, you will also be able

148
00:12:57,690 --> 00:13:03,370
to identify the direction of future price
movements.

149
00:13:03,370 --> 00:13:09,360
Accumulation is often characterized by a ranging-type
market where the price moves sideways.

150
00:13:09,360 --> 00:13:18,079
It is in this zone that banks regularly enter
the market to accumulate their desired position.

151
00:13:18,079 --> 00:13:21,029
Manipulation is the next step after accumulation.

152
00:13:21,029 --> 00:13:25,209
This stage is characterized by false movements.

153
00:13:25,209 --> 00:13:31,970
And as we already discussed, retail traders
are the victims of such market manipulation.

154
00:13:31,970 --> 00:13:36,550
They take positions when they see that there
is a potential breakout.

155
00:13:36,550 --> 00:13:43,040
But it turns out to be just a fake push and
the price then moves in the opposite direction.

156
00:13:43,040 --> 00:13:47,089
If you ever find yourself in this situation,
it's not bad luck.

157
00:13:47,089 --> 00:13:53,850
In this example the banks are trying to enter
or build up a long position.

158
00:13:53,850 --> 00:13:58,290
At the same time, they're also creating selling
pressure.

159
00:13:58,290 --> 00:14:05,310
They will try to "manipulate" retail traders
into first going long, then short.

160
00:14:05,310 --> 00:14:11,759
To follow the banks, you need to identify
the second and hopefully, the final liquidity

161
00:14:11,759 --> 00:14:16,079
clear-out that marks the end of an accumulation
phase

162
00:14:16,079 --> 00:14:23,110
The third stage, is the trend phase, the continuation
in the direction of the initial fake out.

163
00:14:23,110 --> 00:14:30,560
At this point, the banks have accumulated
their position and created the market manipulation.

164
00:14:30,560 --> 00:14:33,529
They no longer try to conceal their presence.

165
00:14:33,529 --> 00:14:40,060
Now, the banks will try to push the price
in a specific direction, which means this

166
00:14:40,060 --> 00:14:43,680
is where a market trend will begin.

167
00:14:43,680 --> 00:14:49,230
And yes, trying to avoid the traps and recognizing
the pattern is difficult.

168
00:14:49,230 --> 00:14:56,060
It takes a lot of research time, and plenty
of live trading and market observing experience,

169
00:14:56,060 --> 00:14:59,889
to notice these stages in real time.

170
00:14:59,889 --> 00:15:05,459
But if you understand how the banks are manipulating
the market, you'll be able to identify the

171
00:15:05,459 --> 00:15:10,390
direction of the market trend that the banks
are trying to push.

172
00:15:10,390 --> 00:15:17,550
Your next task will then be to just follow
the trend, after the second liquidity clear-out.

173
00:15:17,550 --> 00:15:22,839
This doesn't mean you'll never lose when using
this strategy, but it will keep you focused

174
00:15:22,839 --> 00:15:26,029
and ready to win more consistently.

175
00:15:26,029 --> 00:15:31,640
Once you adopt trading strategies that are
in line with those of the big players, your

176
00:15:31,640 --> 00:16:14,319
chances of making profits will go up.

177
00:16:14,319 --> 00:17:38,720
Now, this strategy is designed to take advantage
of market traps.

178
